index.tsx: 

```
import React, { useContext } from "react";
import { Store } from "../state/store";
import { initialState } from "../state/reducers";
import { toggleDrawer } from "../state/actions";

export default function Index() {
  // Get state contexts
  const { state, dispatch } = useContext(Store);
  const onClick = () => {
    const drawerState: boolean = state.drawers.navmenu;
    dispatch(toggleDrawer("navmenu", !drawerState));
  };
  const navmenu: string = initialState.drawers.navmenu.toString();
  return (
    <div>
      <p>Value: {navmenu}</p>
      <button onClick={onClick}>Change</button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Error output:
```
[ error ] { Invariant Violation: Invalid hook call. Hooks can only be called inside of the body of a function component.
```

**What is the expected behavior?**

useContext is being called within the body of a function component. There should be no error. This is literally the only component in the entire app. I am not breaking any of:

1. You might have mismatching versions of React and the renderer (such as React DOM)
2. You might be breaking the Rules of Hooks
3. You might have more than one copy of React in the same app
